# Code Design Review Rule

when including this file in the chat session, perform a focused code design review on all changes before considering the task done.

The purpose of this review is to:
- maintain clean architecture
- reduce technical debt
- prevent unnecessary complexity
- preserve consistency across the codebase
- keep the system maintainable over time

This review focuses on:
- code quality
- architecture consistency
- maintainability
- abstraction quality
- duplication
- simplicity
- reuse

Do NOT focus primarily on:
- security audits
- infrastructure
- deployment
- scalability theory
- edge-case paranoia
unless directly relevant to the implementation.

---

# Review Checklist

## 1. Relevance Cleanup

Check whether the implementation introduced:
- unused functions
- dead code
- obsolete files
- outdated logic
- unnecessary abstractions
- temporary debugging code
- duplicated utilities/components

Remove anything no longer needed.

Prefer deleting over keeping uncertain legacy code.

---

## 2. Existing System Reuse

Before accepting new code, verify:
- whether similar logic already exists
- whether utilities/hooks/services/components can be reused
- whether new abstractions duplicate existing patterns
- whether naming and structure align with the current architecture

Prefer extending existing patterns over creating parallel systems.

---

## 3. Simplicity & Overengineering Review

Actively search for:
- unnecessary abstractions
- premature generalization
- deeply nested logic
- excessive indirection
- large wrappers for small problems
- configuration complexity
- unnecessary state management

Prefer:
- direct flows
- obvious logic
- local reasoning
- minimal abstractions

The simplest maintainable solution is preferred.

---

## 4. Function & Component Design

Verify that:
- functions are small and focused
- components have clear responsibilities
- names explain intent clearly
- logic is composable
- side effects are isolated
- files are not overloaded with responsibilities

Avoid:
- giant functions
- “god components”
- mixed concerns
- hidden side effects

---

## 5. Duplication Review

Search for:
- repeated logic
- repeated UI structures
- repeated transformations
- repeated validation flows
- repeated constants/types

Extract shared logic only when:
- duplication is real
- reuse improves clarity
- abstraction reduces complexity

Avoid abstracting too early.

---

## 6. Architecture Consistency

Ensure new code matches:
- existing project conventions
- folder organization
- naming conventions
- typing strategy
- state management patterns
- API patterns
- error handling style

Do not introduce a new pattern unless clearly justified.

---

## 7. Readability Review

Verify:
- code is easy to scan quickly
- logic flow is obvious
- variable names are meaningful
- files are easy to navigate
- developers can understand intent without excessive comments

Prefer self-explanatory code over clever code.

---

## 8. Final Self-Question

Before finishing, ask internally:

- “Can this be simpler?”
- “Does this abstraction actually help?”
- “Would a new developer understand this quickly?”
- “Did I create something that already exists?”
- “Can anything be deleted?”
- “Is every file/function still justified?”

---

# Output Requirements

At the end of the review, provide a VERY SHORT summary including:

## Review Result
- PASS / NEEDS ATTENTION

## What Was Improved
Short bullets of:
- removed code
- simplifications
- deduplications
- refactors
- reused existing logic

## Open Questions
Only include questions if:
- architectural intent is unclear
- there are multiple valid approaches
- deleting/changing something may affect future plans

Keep questions concise and actionable.

---

# Important Philosophy

Favor:
- clarity
- simplicity
- maintainability
- consistency
- deletion
- focused abstractions

Avoid:
- cleverness
- abstraction for abstraction’s sake
- speculative architecture
- unnecessary extensibility
- defensive overengineering